{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472439"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:58:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:58:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1442"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1442"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0,0.03,0.32,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1442"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31401"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1442"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1442"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17208"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"754"},{"type":"tags","id":"1286"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1577"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2153"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2223"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/31401"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-month-old boy is brought to his general practitioner with a sore wrist which has become more painful over the last three months. His mother also describes him having increasing difficulty with standing on his own. He was born at term with no antenatal or postnatal complications, and he is meeting all developmental milestones. His family members are all well with no significant medical history. His mother is vegetarian.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamination reveals bony tenderness particularly in the hands, with no other significant findings. A hand X-ray is ordered (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypothyroidism","Tuberculosis","Renal osteodystrophy","Osteogenesis imperfecta","Rickets"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERickets\u003C/strong\u003E is a childhood bone disorder caused by a deficiency in Vitamin D, usually from inadequate dietary intake. On X-ray, this patient has cupping, fraying and splaying of the radial and ulnar epiphyses, which are all radiological signs consistent with rickets.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital hypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E can present radiologically with delayed skeletal maturation, stippled epiphysis, and cortical thickening. This patient\u0027s radiological signs would not be expected in congenital hypothyroidism. Clinically, children would present with developmental delay and a disproportionately enlarged head.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E in children presents with weight loss, night sweats, lymphadenopathy and failure to thrive. Skeletal tuberculosis is far less common, usually involving the vertebral bones/joints. Overall, tuberculosis is unlikely to cause wrist pain and the X-ray findings on this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal osteodystrophy\u003C/strong\u003E in children usually results in osteopaenia, fractures, and metaphyseal changes due to hyperparathyroidism and subsequent bone damage. This usually occurs in the setting of chronic renal disease, which is not likely present in this patient given he is reaching developmental milestones and was medically well prior to this presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteogenesis imperfecta\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with bony deformities such as bowing of the knee, muscle weakness, discoloured teeth, discolouration of the sclera, and easily broken bones. Joint pain is not characteristic of osteogenesis imperfecta, and neither is the X-ray shown in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Whilst an uncommon condition, rickets is being seen more often in children, probably because of less time being outside and more time spent playing computer games indoors."],"references":["Gentile C, Chiarelli F. Rickets in Children: An Update. Biomedicines 2021; 9:738-56."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17208"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1442"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18783"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18783","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18783"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7fc1321b-2603-40aa-a3ff-38b5be22d7bc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7fc1321b-2603-40aa-a3ff-38b5be22d7bc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":770,"height":546}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/17208"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-01-08T09:33:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-27T20:53:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1442"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31401"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoj